=== Nihon Shoki ===
The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} states in the 21st year of Emperor Keitai (527?)<ref group="note" name="NihonShokiChronology">The chronology of Emperor Keitai's later years may be three years earlier than recorded due to discrepancies with the Baekje Chronicles (辛亥の変). This shifts the events of 527-528 to 530-531. {{Harv|Iwai Rebellion (Ancient History)|2006}}</ref> that {{ill|Omi no Miko|ja|近江毛野|qq=draft|qq=draft}} led an army of 60,000 across to {{ill|Mimana|ja|任那|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to restore lands seized by {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Iwai, a Tsukushi chieftain, reportedly accepted bribes from Silla to block this mission and gained control over trade routes.<ref>{{Harv|Iwai (Ancient Clans)|2010}}</ref>

The rebellion escalated, but by the 22nd year (528?), Iwai was defeated by the imperial army under {{ill|Mononobe no Arakabi|ja|物部麁鹿火|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and killed in battle.<ref name="Nihon Shoki"/> His son, [[Tsukushi no Katsurako]], surrendered by offering the {{ill|Kasaya Tonogura|ja|糟屋屯倉|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to the imperial court.<ref>{{Harv|Iwai (Ancient Clans)|2010}}</ref>

=== Chikugo no Kuni Fudoki ===
The {{ill|Chikugo no Kuni Fudoki|ja|筑後国風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft}} describes Iwai's Kofun and records that he constructed it during his lifetime but abandoned it after losing his rebellion.<ref>{{Harv|Iwai (Ancient Clans)|2010}}</ref>

== Tomb ==
{{Gallery
|File:岩戸山古墳 石馬.jpg|Stone horse from Iwatoyama Kofun (on display at the Iwatoyama Historical Museum).
}}
The {{ill|Iwatoyama Kofun|ja|岩戸山古墳|1=Iwato-yama Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, identified as Iwai's tomb, is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Yame, Fukuoka|ja|八女市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The largest kofun in northern Kyushu, it dates to the early 6th century.<ref>{{Harv|Iwatoyama Historical Museum|2009}}</ref>

== Legacy ==
Iwai is considered a pivotal figure symbolizing early resistance to Yamato rule, with his tomb illustrating the wealth and power he wielded over northern Kyushu.<ref>{{Harv|Mizutani Chikashi|2013}}</ref>

